Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.720 --> 00:00:07.014
Professor Ramamurti
Shankar: Let me start again

00:00:07.014 --> 00:00:11.390
by reminding you what it is that
was done last time.

00:00:11.390 --> 00:00:15.990
If you say, "Can you summarize
for me in a few words the main

00:00:15.990 --> 00:00:17.730
ideas?"
I would like to do that.

00:00:29.080 --> 00:00:33.820
What I did last time was to
show you how to handle motion in

00:00:33.820 --> 00:00:38.591
more than one dimension.
I picked for it two dimensions

00:00:38.591 --> 00:00:41.720
as the standard way to explain
it.

00:00:41.720 --> 00:00:44.260
By the way, I would like to
make one recommendation.

00:00:44.260 --> 00:00:47.144
If you guys are coming in a
little late, don't worry about

00:00:47.144 --> 00:00:50.058
submitting the homework.
Just come in and settle down,

00:00:50.058 --> 00:00:52.923
because it's very hard to
lecture with this amount of

00:00:52.923 --> 00:00:55.379
traffic.
I do try to start a few minutes

00:00:55.379 --> 00:00:59.018
late, but I also have to finish
a few minutes early so you can

00:00:59.018 --> 00:01:02.353
go to your next class.
Also, people who come in early

00:01:02.353 --> 00:01:05.980
maybe should try to sit in the
middle part of the classroom,

00:01:05.980 --> 00:01:09.730
so the latecomers can come in
without too much disruption.

00:01:09.730 --> 00:01:14.350
So, summary of last time.
If you live in two dimensions

00:01:14.350 --> 00:01:18.180
or more, you've got to use
vectors to describe most things.

00:01:18.180 --> 00:01:22.112
The typical vector is called
V or A or B

00:01:22.112 --> 00:01:26.463
something with an arrow on it.
The most important vector is

00:01:26.463 --> 00:01:30.970
the position vector that tells
you where the object is.

00:01:30.970 --> 00:01:36.725
It's got components which are
x and y that could

00:01:36.725 --> 00:01:40.103
vary with time.
I and J are unit

00:01:40.103 --> 00:01:43.000
vectors in the x and
y directions.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:46.330
You can deal with a vector in
one of two ways.

00:01:46.330 --> 00:01:49.235
You can either think of it as
an arrow and imagine the arrow,

00:01:49.235 --> 00:01:51.850
or you can reduce it to a pair
of numbers, x and

00:01:51.850 --> 00:01:54.394
y.
If you want to add two vectors,

00:01:54.394 --> 00:01:58.099
you can add the arrows by the
rule I gave you or just add the

00:01:58.099 --> 00:02:01.865
components of the two guys to
get the component of the sum and

00:02:01.865 --> 00:02:05.895
likewise for the y.
I mentioned something of

00:02:05.895 --> 00:02:10.656
increasing importance only
later, which is that you are

00:02:10.656 --> 00:02:13.830
free to pick another set of
axes,

00:02:13.830 --> 00:02:16.851
not in the traditional x
and y direction,

00:02:16.851 --> 00:02:20.249
but as an oblique direction.
If you do, the unit vectors are

00:02:20.249 --> 00:02:22.467
called I prime and
J prime,

00:02:22.467 --> 00:02:24.629
the components of the vector
change.

00:02:24.629 --> 00:02:28.318
You can imagine that if a
vector is viewed from an angle,

00:02:28.318 --> 00:02:31.810
then its components will vary
with the perspective.

00:02:31.810 --> 00:02:34.303
So the components of the vector
are not invariant

00:02:34.303 --> 00:02:38.231
characterizations of the vector.
That is, the vector itself has

00:02:38.231 --> 00:02:40.904
a life of its own.
The components come in the

00:02:40.904 --> 00:02:43.262
minute you pick your axis.
It's not enough to say these

00:02:43.262 --> 00:02:44.479
are the components of the
vector;

00:02:44.479 --> 00:02:46.589
you've got to tell me,
"I am working with I and

00:02:46.589 --> 00:02:48.660
J, which I define in the
following manner."

00:02:48.660 --> 00:02:51.769
I gave you a law of
transformation of the

00:02:51.769 --> 00:02:53.880
components;
namely, if the vector has

00:02:53.880 --> 00:02:56.347
components ax and
ay in one reference frame

00:02:56.347 --> 00:02:58.505
and ax prime and
ay prime in another

00:02:58.505 --> 00:03:01.080
reference frame,
how are the two related?

00:03:01.080 --> 00:03:03.820
They come from writing I
prime and J prime in

00:03:03.820 --> 00:03:07.136
terms of I and J,
then sticking it in an

00:03:07.136 --> 00:03:11.210
expression and identifying the
new representation.

00:03:11.210 --> 00:03:13.963
Somehow, when I told you to
invert the transformation,

00:03:13.963 --> 00:03:15.729
some of you had some
difficulty.

00:03:15.729 --> 00:03:19.204
Maybe you didn't realize that
they are just simultaneous

00:03:19.204 --> 00:03:22.255
equations that you solve.
Normally, if I tell you

00:03:22.255 --> 00:03:25.591
3x + 4y = 6,
and 9x + 6y = 14,

00:03:25.591 --> 00:03:28.845
you know how to solve it.
It's like really the same kind

00:03:28.845 --> 00:03:32.075
of problem, except that the 3
and 4 will all be placed by sin

00:03:32.075 --> 00:03:35.360
φ and cos φ but
they are just the numbers.

00:03:35.360 --> 00:03:38.000
You eliminate them the same way
you eliminate them.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:42.589
I've given you a homework
problem where you can try your

00:03:42.589 --> 00:03:44.929
skills.
When you go today and look at

00:03:44.929 --> 00:03:47.176
the homework,
you'll find the problem from

00:03:47.176 --> 00:03:49.424
the textbook,
one extra problem that deals

00:03:49.424 --> 00:03:53.363
with all of this.
Then, I gave you one other very

00:03:53.363 --> 00:03:58.919
important example of a particle
moving in the xy plane.

00:03:58.919 --> 00:04:01.667
x and y can be
whatever you like,

00:04:01.667 --> 00:04:05.012
but I picked a very special
example where x looked

00:04:05.012 --> 00:04:07.699
like this: r times cos
ωt.

00:04:07.699 --> 00:04:13.689
This times I + r
times sin ωt.

00:04:13.689 --> 00:04:16.449
You should go back and remember
what we did.

00:04:16.449 --> 00:04:19.107
If it took you a while to
digest it, I ask you to think

00:04:19.107 --> 00:04:20.868
harder.
This describes a particle

00:04:20.868 --> 00:04:24.139
that's going around in a circle.
We know it's going around in a

00:04:24.139 --> 00:04:26.790
circle because if I find the
length of this vector,

00:04:26.790 --> 00:04:29.735
which is the x-square
part, plus the y-square

00:04:29.735 --> 00:04:32.019
part, I just get r^(2) at
all times,

00:04:32.019 --> 00:04:34.690
because sine square plus cosine
square is one.

00:04:34.690 --> 00:04:37.529
So we know it's moving on a
circle of radius r.

00:04:37.529 --> 00:04:41.285
Furthermore,
as time increases,

00:04:41.285 --> 00:04:48.170
the angle, ωt,
is increasing in this fashion.

00:04:48.170 --> 00:04:51.079
Omega is called the angle of
velocity.

00:04:51.079 --> 00:04:54.211
I related it to the time
period, which is the time it

00:04:54.211 --> 00:04:56.319
takes to go around a full
circle,

00:04:56.319 --> 00:05:00.411
by saying once you've done a
full circle, ωt better

00:05:00.411 --> 00:05:03.435
be 2π.
So this new quantity ω,

00:05:03.435 --> 00:05:06.860
which may be new to you,
is related to the time period.

00:05:06.860 --> 00:05:10.459
How long does it take to go one
round in this fashion?

00:05:10.459 --> 00:05:16.279
You're also free to write it in
terms of the frequency.

00:05:16.279 --> 00:05:18.899
The time period and frequency
are reciprocals.

00:05:18.899 --> 00:05:22.294
If it takes you 1/60 of a
second to go around once,

00:05:22.294 --> 00:05:24.670
then you do it 60 times a
second.

00:05:24.670 --> 00:05:28.500
Omega is really very simple
quantity.

00:05:28.500 --> 00:05:31.437
It's related to the frequency
with which you go around the

00:05:31.437 --> 00:05:33.550
circle but is multiplied by
2π.

00:05:33.550 --> 00:05:35.852
Why is that?
Frequencies,

00:05:35.852 --> 00:05:39.633
how many times you go around,
and 2π is the rate at

00:05:39.633 --> 00:05:41.980
which the angle is being
changed.

00:05:41.980 --> 00:05:45.112
But if every revolution is
worth 2π radians,

00:05:45.112 --> 00:05:48.490
then 2πf is the number
of radians per second.

00:05:48.490 --> 00:05:51.310
f is revolutions per
second and 2πf is

00:05:51.310 --> 00:05:54.144
radians per second.
It's called the angle of

00:05:54.144 --> 00:05:56.519
velocity.
The most important result from

00:05:56.519 --> 00:05:59.079
last time was that if you took
this r,

00:05:59.079 --> 00:06:04.216
and you took two derivatives of
this to find the acceleration,

00:06:04.216 --> 00:06:07.500
d2r over
dt^(2),

00:06:07.500 --> 00:06:11.643
try to do this in your head.
If you took the two derivatives

00:06:11.643 --> 00:06:14.493
of this guy, first time it will
become -ω,

00:06:14.493 --> 00:06:17.528
sin ωt;
second time it will become

00:06:17.528 --> 00:06:20.622
-ω^(2) cos ωt.
In other words,

00:06:20.622 --> 00:06:22.740
it will become -ω^(2)
times itself.

00:06:22.740 --> 00:06:25.941
Same thing there.
The final result is the

00:06:25.941 --> 00:06:29.779
acceleration is -ω^(2)
times the position.

00:06:29.779 --> 00:06:34.139
That means the acceleration is
pointing towards the center of

00:06:34.139 --> 00:06:37.410
the circle and it has a
magnitude a.

00:06:37.410 --> 00:06:39.951
When I draw something without
an arrow, I'm talking about the

00:06:39.951 --> 00:06:44.540
magnitude.
It is just ω^(2)r.

00:06:44.540 --> 00:06:49.408
I have shown you yesterday that
the speed of the particle as it

00:06:49.408 --> 00:06:53.019
goes around the circle is this
(ωr).

00:06:53.019 --> 00:06:55.740
Again, you should make sure you
know how to derive this.

00:06:55.740 --> 00:06:58.940
You can do it any way you like.
You can take one full circle

00:06:58.940 --> 00:07:01.204
and realize the distance
traveled is 2πr,

00:07:01.204 --> 00:07:03.279
divide by the time and you will
get this.

00:07:03.279 --> 00:07:05.828
Another way,
take the derivative of this,

00:07:05.828 --> 00:07:09.397
get the velocity vector and you
notice his magnitude is a

00:07:09.397 --> 00:07:12.519
constant and the constant will
be ωr.

00:07:12.519 --> 00:07:18.085
Whichever way you do it,
you can then rewrite this as

00:07:18.085 --> 00:07:23.753
v^(2) over r.
This is called the centripetal

00:07:23.753 --> 00:07:24.950
acceleration.

00:07:30.519 --> 00:07:33.069
This is the acceleration
directed toward the center.

00:07:33.069 --> 00:07:35.089
I told you these are very
important results.

00:07:35.089 --> 00:07:36.810
You've got to get this in your
head.

00:07:36.810 --> 00:07:39.070
Whenever you see a particle
moving in a circle,

00:07:39.070 --> 00:07:40.790
even if it's at a constant
speed,

00:07:40.790 --> 00:07:44.102
it has an acceleration,
v^(2) over r

00:07:44.102 --> 00:07:47.888
directed towards the center.
This formula doesn't tell you

00:07:47.888 --> 00:07:50.800
which way it's pointing,
because it's a scaler;

00:07:50.800 --> 00:07:55.376
it's not a vector equation.
If you want to write it as a

00:07:55.376 --> 00:07:59.702
vector equation,
you want to write it as

00:07:59.702 --> 00:08:05.914
v^(2) over r
minus--I want to say that it's

00:08:05.914 --> 00:08:11.350
pointing in the direction toward
the center.

00:08:11.350 --> 00:08:16.136
So sometimes what we do is we
introduce a little vector here

00:08:16.136 --> 00:08:20.459
called e_r.
I'll tell you more about it

00:08:20.459 --> 00:08:22.432
later.
e_r is a

00:08:22.432 --> 00:08:26.049
vector at each point of length
one pointing radially away from

00:08:26.049 --> 00:08:28.951
the center.
It's like the unit vector

00:08:28.951 --> 00:08:30.960
I.
Unit vector I points

00:08:30.960 --> 00:08:33.059
away from the origin in the
x direction.

00:08:33.059 --> 00:08:34.929
J points away from the
origin in the y

00:08:34.929 --> 00:08:36.705
direction.
e_r is not a

00:08:36.705 --> 00:08:38.264
fixed vector.
At each point,

00:08:38.264 --> 00:08:41.988
e_r is a
different vector pointing in the

00:08:41.988 --> 00:08:46.394
radial direction of length one.
The advantage of introducing

00:08:46.394 --> 00:08:51.073
that guy is that if you like,
I can now write an equation for

00:08:51.073 --> 00:08:54.861
the acceleration as a vector.
The magnitude is v^(2)

00:08:54.861 --> 00:08:56.301
over r.
The direction is

00:08:56.301 --> 00:09:00.019
-e_r.
So e_r is a

00:09:00.019 --> 00:09:04.120
new entity I've introduced for
convenience.

00:09:04.120 --> 00:09:06.919
It plays a big role in
gravitation, in the Coulomb

00:09:06.919 --> 00:09:09.171
interaction.
It's good to have a vector

00:09:09.171 --> 00:09:11.850
pointing in the radial direction
of length one.

00:09:11.850 --> 00:09:14.649
That's what it is.
That's really the heart of what

00:09:14.649 --> 00:09:17.088
I did last time.
Then we did some projectile

00:09:17.088 --> 00:09:18.638
problems.
You shoot something,

00:09:18.638 --> 00:09:21.364
you should know when it will
land, where it will land,

00:09:21.364 --> 00:09:24.090
with what speed it will land,
how high it will go.

00:09:24.090 --> 00:09:27.238
I assume that those problems
are not that difficult and I've

00:09:27.238 --> 00:09:32.532
given you a lot of practice.
Now I'm going to move to the

00:09:32.532 --> 00:09:37.279
really important and central
topic.

00:09:37.279 --> 00:09:39.840
I guess you can guess what that
is.

00:09:39.840 --> 00:09:42.250
We're going to talk about
Newton's laws.

00:09:42.250 --> 00:09:47.194
This is a big day in your life.
This is when you learn the laws

00:09:47.194 --> 00:09:50.893
in terms of which you can
understand and explain a large

00:09:50.893 --> 00:09:53.701
number of phenomena.
In fact, until we do

00:09:53.701 --> 00:09:56.413
electricity and magnetism the
next semester,

00:09:56.413 --> 00:10:00.259
everything's going to be based
on just the laws of Newton.

00:10:00.259 --> 00:10:03.811
It's really amazing that
somebody could condense that

00:10:03.811 --> 00:10:06.612
much information into a few,
namely three,

00:10:06.612 --> 00:10:09.786
different laws.
That's what we're going to talk

00:10:09.786 --> 00:10:11.929
about.
Let's start.

00:10:11.929 --> 00:10:15.289
Your reaction may be that
you've seen Newton's laws,

00:10:15.289 --> 00:10:19.018
you applied them in school.
I've got to tell you that I

00:10:19.018 --> 00:10:22.721
realized fairly late in life
they are more subtle than I

00:10:22.721 --> 00:10:25.905
imagined the first time.
It's one thing to plug in all

00:10:25.905 --> 00:10:28.117
the numbers and say,
"I know Newton's laws and I

00:10:28.117 --> 00:10:30.948
know how they work."
But as you get older and you

00:10:30.948 --> 00:10:34.258
have a lot of spare time,
you think about what you are

00:10:34.258 --> 00:10:36.251
doing,
which is something I have the

00:10:36.251 --> 00:10:38.866
luxury of doing right now,
and I realized this is more

00:10:38.866 --> 00:10:41.006
tricky.
I want to share some of that

00:10:41.006 --> 00:10:44.535
with you so you can fast forward
and get the understanding it

00:10:44.535 --> 00:10:47.199
took me much longer to get.
That's what I'm going to

00:10:47.199 --> 00:10:49.110
emphasize, more than just
plugging in the numbers.

00:10:49.110 --> 00:10:52.689
Of course, we have to also know
how to plug in the numbers so we

00:10:52.689 --> 00:10:56.323
can pass all the tests,
but it's good to understand the

00:10:56.323 --> 00:10:59.179
nature of the edifice set up by
Newton.

00:10:59.179 --> 00:11:03.610
First statement by Newton--I
don't feel like writing it down.

00:11:03.610 --> 00:11:07.160
It's too long and everybody
knows what the law is.

00:11:07.160 --> 00:11:11.650
It's called the Law of Inertia.
Let me just say it and talk

00:11:11.650 --> 00:11:15.854
about it.
The Law of Inertia says that,

00:11:15.854 --> 00:11:22.421
"If a body has no forces acting
on it, then it will remain at

00:11:22.421 --> 00:11:26.799
rest if it was at rest to begin
with,

00:11:26.799 --> 00:11:30.564
or if it had a velocity to
begin with, it will maintain

00:11:30.564 --> 00:11:33.587
that velocity."
One way to say it is,

00:11:33.587 --> 00:11:38.401
every body will continue to
remain in a state of rest or

00:11:38.401 --> 00:11:41.639
uniform motion in a straight
line.

00:11:41.639 --> 00:11:44.782
That's another way of saying
maintaining velocity if it's not

00:11:44.782 --> 00:11:48.441
acted upon by a force.
What makes the law surprising

00:11:48.441 --> 00:11:53.574
is that if I only gave you half
the law, namely every body will

00:11:53.574 --> 00:11:57.880
remain at rest if it's not acted
upon by a force,

00:11:57.880 --> 00:11:59.565
you will say, "That's fine.
I accept that,

00:11:59.565 --> 00:12:01.523
because here's something.
You leave it there,

00:12:01.523 --> 00:12:03.950
it doesn't move.
It's not a big surprise."

00:12:03.950 --> 00:12:06.519
People were used to that from
the time of Aristotle.

00:12:06.519 --> 00:12:10.570
But Aristotle used to think
that if you want something to

00:12:10.570 --> 00:12:14.259
move, there has to be some
agency making it move.

00:12:14.259 --> 00:12:16.549
That agency you could call
force.

00:12:16.549 --> 00:12:20.335
The great discovery that
Galileo and Newton made is that

00:12:20.335 --> 00:12:23.915
you don't need a force for a
body to move at constant

00:12:23.915 --> 00:12:27.210
velocity.
It's very clear you don't need

00:12:27.210 --> 00:12:31.929
a force if something is doing
nothing, just sitting there.

00:12:31.929 --> 00:12:35.067
The fact that you don't need a
force for it to move forever at

00:12:35.067 --> 00:12:36.970
a given speed in a given
direction,

00:12:36.970 --> 00:12:39.724
that's not obvious,
because in daily life you don't

00:12:39.724 --> 00:12:40.974
see that.
In daily life,

00:12:40.974 --> 00:12:43.599
everything seems to come to
rest unless you push it or you

00:12:43.599 --> 00:12:45.580
pull it or you exert some kind
of force.

00:12:45.580 --> 00:12:50.965
But we all know that the reason
things come to a halt when you

00:12:50.965 --> 00:12:53.306
push them is,
there eventually is some

00:12:53.306 --> 00:12:55.549
friction or drag or something
bringing them to rest.

00:12:55.549 --> 00:12:58.256
Somehow, if you could
manufacture a really smooth

00:12:58.256 --> 00:13:01.132
frictionless surface,
that if you took a hockey puck

00:13:01.132 --> 00:13:04.460
or something and an air cushion
and you give it a push,

00:13:04.460 --> 00:13:08.090
in some idealized world,
it'll travel forever.

00:13:08.090 --> 00:13:13.730
So it's hard to realize that in
the terrestrial situation.

00:13:13.730 --> 00:13:17.049
But Galileo already managed to
find examples where things would

00:13:17.049 --> 00:13:19.029
roll on for a very,
very long time.

00:13:19.029 --> 00:13:21.822
Nowadays, if you go to outer
space, you can check for

00:13:21.822 --> 00:13:23.970
yourself that if you throw
something out,

00:13:23.970 --> 00:13:26.870
it just goes on forever without
your intervention.

00:13:26.870 --> 00:13:31.490
It's in the nature of things to
go at a constant velocity.

00:13:31.490 --> 00:13:35.720
They don't need your help to do
that.

00:13:35.720 --> 00:13:40.548
You have to be careful that
this first law of Newton is not

00:13:40.548 --> 00:13:44.258
valid for everybody.
In fact, I'll give an example

00:13:44.258 --> 00:13:48.470
in your own life where you will
find that this law doesn't work.

00:13:48.470 --> 00:13:52.689
Here is the situation.
You go on an airplane and then

00:13:52.689 --> 00:13:56.981
after the usual delays,
the plane begins to accelerate

00:13:56.981 --> 00:13:59.595
down the runway.
At that instant,

00:13:59.595 --> 00:14:03.494
if you leave anything on the
floor, you know it's no longer

00:14:03.494 --> 00:14:05.379
yours.
It's going to slide down and

00:14:05.379 --> 00:14:07.940
the guy in the last row is going
to collect everything.

00:14:07.940 --> 00:14:12.315
Why is that?
Because we find in that plane,

00:14:12.315 --> 00:14:16.126
when objects are left at what
you think is at rest with no

00:14:16.126 --> 00:14:19.632
external agency acting on them,
they all slide backwards

00:14:19.632 --> 00:14:21.430
towards the rear end of the
plane.

00:14:21.430 --> 00:14:24.663
That happens during takeoff.
That doesn't happen in flight,

00:14:24.663 --> 00:14:28.319
but it happens during takeoff.
That is an example of a person

00:14:28.319 --> 00:14:31.629
for whom the Law of Inertia does
not work.

00:14:31.629 --> 00:14:34.679
This is something you guys may
not have realized.

00:14:34.679 --> 00:14:36.929
Newton's laws are not for
everybody.

00:14:36.929 --> 00:14:40.730
You have to be what's called an
"inertial observer."

00:14:40.730 --> 00:14:45.331
If you're an inertial observer,
then in your system of

00:14:45.331 --> 00:14:50.019
reference, objects left at rest
will remain at rest.

00:14:50.019 --> 00:14:53.646
The plane that's ready to take
off or is taking off is not such

00:14:53.646 --> 00:14:55.953
a system.
The Earth seems to be a pretty

00:14:55.953 --> 00:14:58.337
good inertial system,
because on the ground,

00:14:58.337 --> 00:15:00.500
you leave something,
it stays there.

00:15:04.530 --> 00:15:07.084
It depends on what you leave.
If you leave your iPod,

00:15:07.084 --> 00:15:08.909
it's not going to stay there
for very long.

00:15:08.909 --> 00:15:11.721
But then you can trace it to
some external forces,

00:15:11.721 --> 00:15:15.302
which are carrying your iPod.
But if you don't do anything,

00:15:15.302 --> 00:15:18.299
things stay.
Here is the main point.

00:15:18.299 --> 00:15:20.924
The point of Newton is,
two things in the Law of

00:15:20.924 --> 00:15:23.269
Inertia, which one may think is
trivial.

00:15:23.269 --> 00:15:26.327
First, free velocity,
constant velocity can be

00:15:26.327 --> 00:15:29.250
obtained for free without doing
anything.

00:15:29.250 --> 00:15:31.889
There are people for whom this
is true.

00:15:31.889 --> 00:15:33.189
For example,
in outer space,

00:15:33.189 --> 00:15:35.293
you've got an astronaut.
You send something,

00:15:35.293 --> 00:15:39.340
you'll find it goes on forever.
Here's another thing.

00:15:39.340 --> 00:15:42.946
If you find one inertial
observer, namely one person for

00:15:42.946 --> 00:15:46.948
whom this Law of Inertia works,
I can manufacture for you an

00:15:46.948 --> 00:15:50.560
infinite number of other people
for whom this is true.

00:15:50.560 --> 00:15:54.217
Who are these other people?
Do you know what I'm talking

00:15:54.217 --> 00:15:57.000
about?
If I give you one observer for

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:01.962
whom the Law of Inertia is true,
I say that others for whom is

00:16:01.962 --> 00:16:04.360
also true.
Yes?

00:16:04.360 --> 00:16:05.939
Student:
[inaudible]

00:16:05.939 --> 00:16:09.340
Professor Ramamurti
Shankar: Did you hear that?

00:16:09.340 --> 00:16:12.000
Let me repeat that.
First of all,

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:16.018
if the Law of Inertia is valid
for me, it's valid for other

00:16:16.018 --> 00:16:19.759
people in the same room at rest
with respect to me.

00:16:19.759 --> 00:16:21.845
Because if I think it's not
moving, you think it's not

00:16:21.845 --> 00:16:23.620
moving.
That's just fine.

00:16:23.620 --> 00:16:27.058
But suppose you are in a train
and you're moving past me and

00:16:27.058 --> 00:16:30.327
you look at this piece of chalk.
Of course, everything in my

00:16:30.327 --> 00:16:34.079
room is going backwards for you.
But things which were at rest

00:16:34.079 --> 00:16:37.688
will move at a constant
velocity, opposite of the

00:16:37.688 --> 00:16:40.769
velocity that you have relative
to me.

00:16:40.769 --> 00:16:45.418
You will find that objects that
are at constant initial velocity

00:16:45.418 --> 00:16:49.467
maintain the velocity.
If I am an inertial observer,

00:16:49.467 --> 00:16:54.257
another person moving relative
to me at constant velocity will

00:16:54.257 --> 00:16:58.399
also be an inertial observer.
Why?

00:16:58.399 --> 00:17:02.238
Because any velocity I ascribe
to a particle or an object,

00:17:02.238 --> 00:17:06.412
you will add a certain constant
to it by the law of composition

00:17:06.412 --> 00:17:08.920
of velocity.
All velocities I see you will

00:17:08.920 --> 00:17:11.930
add a certain number to get the
velocities according to you.

00:17:11.930 --> 00:17:15.732
But adding a constant velocity
to objects does not change the

00:17:15.732 --> 00:17:19.218
fact that those which were
maintaining constant velocity

00:17:19.218 --> 00:17:21.690
still maintain a constant
velocity.

00:17:21.690 --> 00:17:23.640
It's a different constant
velocity.

00:17:23.640 --> 00:17:25.853
In particular,
the things that I say are at

00:17:25.853 --> 00:17:28.964
rest, you will say are moving
backwards at the velocity that

00:17:28.964 --> 00:17:31.936
you have relative to me.
Things that I say are going at

00:17:31.936 --> 00:17:34.279
50 miles per hour you may say
are going at 80.

00:17:34.279 --> 00:17:37.650
But 50 is a constant and 80 is
a constant.

00:17:37.650 --> 00:17:41.014
Therefore, it's not that
there's only one fortunate

00:17:41.014 --> 00:17:44.337
family of inertial observers.
There's infinite number of

00:17:44.337 --> 00:17:46.860
them, but they're all moving
relative to each other at

00:17:46.860 --> 00:17:49.528
constant velocity.
If the Earth is an inertial

00:17:49.528 --> 00:17:52.494
frame of reference,
if you go in a train relative

00:17:52.494 --> 00:17:56.140
to the Earth at constant
velocity, you're also inertial.

00:17:56.140 --> 00:17:59.882
But if you go on a plane which
is accelerating,

00:17:59.882 --> 00:18:03.720
you're no longer inertial.
That's the main point.

00:18:03.720 --> 00:18:06.700
The point is that there are
inertial frames of reference.

00:18:06.700 --> 00:18:11.490
You must know the Earth is not
precisely inertial.

00:18:11.490 --> 00:18:13.200
The Earth has an acceleration.

00:18:16.349 --> 00:18:18.820
Can you tell me why I'm sure
the Earth has an acceleration?

00:18:23.040 --> 00:18:24.947
Yes?
Student:

00:18:24.947 --> 00:18:25.579
Because it's moving in a
circle.

00:18:25.579 --> 00:18:27.098
Professor Ramamurti
Shankar: It's going around

00:18:27.098 --> 00:18:28.799
the Sun.
Let's imagine it's a circular

00:18:28.799 --> 00:18:30.647
orbit.
Then we've just shown here,

00:18:30.647 --> 00:18:32.880
it's an accelerated frame of
reference.

00:18:32.880 --> 00:18:35.905
It just turns out that if you
put the v^(2) and you put

00:18:35.905 --> 00:18:38.040
the r,
and r is 93 million

00:18:38.040 --> 00:18:41.034
miles, you will find the
acceleration is small enough for

00:18:41.034 --> 00:18:43.077
us to ignore.
But there are effects of the

00:18:43.077 --> 00:18:45.069
Earth's acceleration,
which we'll demonstrate.

00:18:45.069 --> 00:18:48.185
The Focault pendulum is one
example where you can see that

00:18:48.185 --> 00:18:50.589
the Earth is rotating around its
own axis.

00:18:50.589 --> 00:18:53.450
Then, the fact that the Earth
is going around the Sun.

00:18:53.450 --> 00:18:55.642
All of them mean it's really
not inertial,

00:18:55.642 --> 00:18:57.460
but it's approximately
inertial.

00:18:57.460 --> 00:19:00.781
But if you go to outer space
nowadays, you can find truly

00:19:00.781 --> 00:19:06.339
inertial frames of reference.
That's the first law.

00:19:06.339 --> 00:19:07.584
The first law,
if you want,

00:19:07.584 --> 00:19:09.977
if you want to say,
"Okay what's the summary of all

00:19:09.977 --> 00:19:12.453
of this?"
The summary is that constant

00:19:12.453 --> 00:19:14.769
velocity doesn't require
anything.

00:19:14.769 --> 00:19:19.045
The reason it looks like a
tautology, because you look

00:19:19.045 --> 00:19:23.319
around, nothing seems to have
its velocity forever.

00:19:23.319 --> 00:19:24.973
Then you say,
"Oh, that's because there's a

00:19:24.973 --> 00:19:27.066
force acting on it."
It looks like a tautology

00:19:27.066 --> 00:19:29.812
because you're never able to
show me something that moves

00:19:29.812 --> 00:19:32.846
forever at a constant velocity,
because every time you don't

00:19:32.846 --> 00:19:34.554
find such a thing,
I give an excuse,

00:19:34.554 --> 00:19:37.349
namely, a force is acting.
But it's not a big con,

00:19:37.349 --> 00:19:40.410
because you can set up
experiments in free space far

00:19:40.410 --> 00:19:42.546
from everything,
where objects will,

00:19:42.546 --> 00:19:44.750
in fact, maintain their
velocity forever.

00:19:44.750 --> 00:19:48.330
That's a possibility.
It's a useful concept on the

00:19:48.330 --> 00:19:51.640
Earth, because Earth is
approximately inertial.

00:19:51.640 --> 00:19:56.789
Now, we have come to the second
law, which is "the law."

00:19:56.789 --> 00:20:00.059
This is the law that we all
memorize and learn.

00:20:00.059 --> 00:20:03.467
It says that,
"If a body has an acceleration,

00:20:03.467 --> 00:20:07.570
then you need a force and the
relation of the force to

00:20:07.570 --> 00:20:11.519
acceleration is this thing:
F = ma" Now,

00:20:11.519 --> 00:20:14.309
I have to say a few words about
units.

00:20:14.309 --> 00:20:18.390
Acceleration is measured in
meters per second squared.

00:20:18.390 --> 00:20:22.759
Mass is measured in kilograms.
So, the way to measure force is

00:20:22.759 --> 00:20:24.809
in kilogram meters per second
squared.

00:20:24.809 --> 00:20:28.236
But we get tired of saying that
long expression,

00:20:28.236 --> 00:20:31.589
so we're going to call that a
Newton, right?

00:20:31.589 --> 00:20:34.764
If you invented it,
we'd call it whatever your name

00:20:34.764 --> 00:20:38.319
is, but this is the guy who
invented it, so it's called a

00:20:38.319 --> 00:20:41.049
Newton, usually denoted by a
capital N.

00:20:41.049 --> 00:20:46.162
A typical problem that you may
have done in your first pass at

00:20:46.162 --> 00:20:49.619
Newton's law,
someone tells you a force of 36

00:20:49.619 --> 00:20:53.450
Newtons is acting on a mass of
whatever, 4 kilograms;

00:20:53.450 --> 00:20:56.365
what's the acceleration?
You divide and you find it's 9

00:20:56.365 --> 00:20:58.708
and you say, "Okay,
I know what to do with Newton's

00:20:58.708 --> 00:21:00.787
laws."
That's where I want to tell you

00:21:00.787 --> 00:21:03.299
that it's actually more
complicated than that.

00:21:03.299 --> 00:21:06.740
Let's really look at this
equation.

00:21:06.740 --> 00:21:09.077
Take yourself back to
1600-whatever,

00:21:09.077 --> 00:21:11.950
whenever Newton was inventing
these laws.

00:21:11.950 --> 00:21:13.490
You don't know any of these
laws.

00:21:13.490 --> 00:21:15.980
You have an intuitive
definition of force.

00:21:15.980 --> 00:21:19.030
You sort of know what force is.
Somebody pushes you or pulls

00:21:19.030 --> 00:21:20.460
you.
That's a force.

00:21:20.460 --> 00:21:25.190
Suddenly, you are told there is
a law.

00:21:25.190 --> 00:21:28.673
Are you better off in any way?
"Can you do anything with this

00:21:28.673 --> 00:21:29.900
law?"
is what I'm asking you.

00:21:29.900 --> 00:21:32.001
What can you do with this law?
I give you Newton's law and

00:21:32.001 --> 00:21:34.010
say, "Good luck."
What will you do?

00:21:34.010 --> 00:21:38.680
What does it help you predict?
Can you even tell if it's true?

00:21:38.680 --> 00:21:41.890
Here's a body that's moving,
right?

00:21:41.890 --> 00:21:45.460
I want you to tell me,
is Newton right?

00:21:45.460 --> 00:21:48.206
How are we going to check that?
Well, you want to measure the

00:21:48.206 --> 00:21:50.579
left-hand side and you want to
measure the right-hand side.

00:21:50.579 --> 00:21:52.526
If they're equal,
maybe you will say the law is

00:21:52.526 --> 00:21:56.332
working.
What can you measure in this

00:21:56.332 --> 00:21:58.214
equation?
Student:

00:21:58.214 --> 00:21:59.700
[inaudible]
Professor Ramamurti

00:21:59.700 --> 00:22:01.631
Shankar: Pardon me?
Student:

00:22:01.631 --> 00:22:03.275
Force and acceleration.
Professor Ramamurti

00:22:03.275 --> 00:22:05.599
Shankar: All right.
Let's start with acceleration.

00:22:05.599 --> 00:22:09.293
What's your plan for measuring
acceleration if some little

00:22:09.293 --> 00:22:12.400
thing is moving?
What do you need to measure it?

00:22:12.400 --> 00:22:13.670
Student:
The change in velocity over the

00:22:13.670 --> 00:22:14.774
change [inaudible]
Professor Ramamurti

00:22:14.774 --> 00:22:16.895
Shankar: Right,
but what instruments will you

00:22:16.895 --> 00:22:19.192
need to measure it?
You are supposed to really

00:22:19.192 --> 00:22:21.420
measure it.
What will you ask me for?

00:22:21.420 --> 00:22:24.339
Student: A watch.
Professor Ramamurti

00:22:24.339 --> 00:22:26.880
Shankar: A watch?
Yes.

00:22:26.880 --> 00:22:27.686
Student:
[inaudible]

00:22:27.686 --> 00:22:29.299
Professor Ramamurti
Shankar: And what else?

00:22:29.299 --> 00:22:29.708
Student:
[inaudible]

00:22:29.708 --> 00:22:30.430
Professor Ramamurti
Shankar: A ruler?

00:22:30.430 --> 00:22:33.440
Okay.
That's right.

00:22:33.440 --> 00:22:35.320
You don't mean Queen Elizabeth,
right?

00:22:35.320 --> 00:22:39.864
You mean-- Very good.
What you really want--a ruler

00:22:39.864 --> 00:22:42.809
may not be enough,
but maybe it's enough.

00:22:42.809 --> 00:22:45.642
So here's the long ruler and
here's this thing moving,

00:22:45.642 --> 00:22:49.627
right?
You ask for a Rolex so here's

00:22:49.627 --> 00:22:52.630
your watch.
It's telling time.

00:22:52.630 --> 00:22:56.590
Tell me exactly what you want
to do to measure acceleration.

00:22:56.590 --> 00:23:00.540
What do you have to do?
I want the acceleration now.

00:23:00.540 --> 00:23:06.050
What will you measure?
Okay, you go ahead.

00:23:06.050 --> 00:23:08.414
You can try.
Student:

00:23:08.414 --> 00:23:10.623
[inaudible]
Student:

00:23:10.623 --> 00:23:14.022
[inaudible]
I would start with the object

00:23:14.022 --> 00:23:18.271
at rest and then [inaudible]
Professor Ramamurti

00:23:18.271 --> 00:23:23.030
Shankar: It may not be at
rest to begin with.

00:23:23.030 --> 00:23:25.830
It's doing its thing.
It's going at some speed.

00:23:25.830 --> 00:23:27.481
Yes?
Student:

00:23:27.481 --> 00:23:30.503
Measure the distance it travels
over a constant interval of

00:23:30.503 --> 00:23:31.413
time?
Professor Ramamurti

00:23:31.413 --> 00:23:32.400
Shankar: That'll give you
the velocity.

00:23:32.400 --> 00:23:34.853
Student:
Well, if you do distance after

00:23:34.853 --> 00:23:38.233
one second versus distance over
the next second versus distance

00:23:38.233 --> 00:23:40.960
over a third second,
you see how it increases.

00:23:40.960 --> 00:23:41.759
Professor Ramamurti
Shankar: Good,

00:23:41.759 --> 00:23:43.529
in principle.
Let me repeat what he said.

00:23:43.529 --> 00:23:45.939
He said, first,
let it go a little distance,

00:23:45.939 --> 00:23:49.329
take the distance over time.
That gives you the velocity now.

00:23:49.329 --> 00:23:51.871
Let it go a little more,
that gives you the velocity

00:23:51.871 --> 00:23:53.893
later.
Take the difference of the two

00:23:53.893 --> 00:23:56.925
velocities and divide by the
difference of the two times,

00:23:56.925 --> 00:23:58.819
and you've got the
acceleration.

00:23:58.819 --> 00:24:03.230
Of course, you have allowed it
to move a finite distance in a

00:24:03.230 --> 00:24:06.066
finite time.
What you should imagine doing

00:24:06.066 --> 00:24:08.994
is making these three
measurements more and more

00:24:08.994 --> 00:24:11.359
quickly.
You need three positional

00:24:11.359 --> 00:24:13.354
measurements.
Now, a little later,

00:24:13.354 --> 00:24:16.202
and a little later later,
because between the first and

00:24:16.202 --> 00:24:17.530
second,
you get a velocity,

00:24:17.530 --> 00:24:19.509
the second and third you get
another velocity.

00:24:19.509 --> 00:24:23.909
Their difference divided by the
difference in times is going to

00:24:23.909 --> 00:24:27.563
be the acceleration.
But if you imagine making these

00:24:27.563 --> 00:24:30.467
measurements more and more and
more quickly,

00:24:30.467 --> 00:24:33.844
in the end, you can measure
what you can say is the

00:24:33.844 --> 00:24:37.168
acceleration now.
That's the meaning of the limit

00:24:37.168 --> 00:24:39.222
in calculus.
You take Δx and you

00:24:39.222 --> 00:24:40.695
take Δt.
What's the meaning of

00:24:40.695 --> 00:24:41.900
Δx and Δt going
to 0?

00:24:41.900 --> 00:24:44.930
It means, measure them as
quickly as you can.

00:24:44.930 --> 00:24:47.392
In the real world,
no one's going to measure it

00:24:47.392 --> 00:24:49.855
instantaneously,
but we can make the difference

00:24:49.855 --> 00:24:52.071
as small as we like.
Mathematically,

00:24:52.071 --> 00:24:54.029
we can make it 0.
In that limit,

00:24:54.029 --> 00:24:56.130
we can measure velocity right
now.

00:24:56.130 --> 00:25:00.505
That means we can also measure
velocity slightly later and make

00:25:00.505 --> 00:25:04.670
the slightly later come as close
to right now as we want.

00:25:04.670 --> 00:25:06.970
Then, that ratio will give you
acceleration.

00:25:06.970 --> 00:25:10.989
Acceleration is the easiest
thing to measure of these three

00:25:10.989 --> 00:25:13.637
quantities.
We all have a good intuitive

00:25:13.637 --> 00:25:15.759
feeling for what acceleration
is.

00:25:15.759 --> 00:25:19.799
You want to test if what Newton
told you is right.

00:25:19.799 --> 00:25:23.377
You see an object in motion,
you find a and you give

00:25:23.377 --> 00:25:26.769
a a certain numerical
value, 10 meters per second

00:25:26.769 --> 00:25:29.036
squared.
But that's not yet testing the

00:25:29.036 --> 00:25:31.530
equation, because you've got to
find both sides.

00:25:31.530 --> 00:25:36.720
What about the mass?
What's the mass of this object?

00:25:40.170 --> 00:25:42.410
Anybody want to try from this
section here?

00:25:42.410 --> 00:25:44.131
Yes?
Student:

00:25:44.131 --> 00:25:47.616
You could use some sort of a
standard unit of mass and then a

00:25:47.616 --> 00:25:50.230
balance to measure the mass of
something else,

00:25:50.230 --> 00:25:53.367
like put it at a certain
distance from the fulcrum on a

00:25:53.367 --> 00:25:56.039
scale and figure out the
relative mass.

